body:
Consider the following queries on the [users collection](fts-sort-index)
given an additional document with a multi-typed array in field `c`:

```json
db.users.insertOne({
  "_id": 7,
  "a": UUID("03e32aa9-1cbd-43b8-b9d6-18b171a03cc7"),
  "b": "hello",
  "c": [ false, null, 15 ]
})
```

The following queries search field `b` for the string `hello`
using the [text](text-ref) operator and sorts the results by field `c`.

**Default:**

Default

> **Note:** Setting `noData: lowest` in your [sort syntax](sort-syntax-ref)
> is the same as the default.

**Ascending-sort:**

Ascending Sort

For an ascending sort, MongoDB Search uses the element with the
lowest BSON (Binary Javascript Object Notation) type to represent the multi-typed array.
By default, MongoDB Search considers null or missing values
as the lowest BSON (Binary Javascript Object Notation) value. Therefore,
MongoDB Search uses `null` to represent the multi-typed array for
the document with `_id: 7` and returns this document at
the top of the results along with other null and missing values.

To learn more, see [Sort by Null and Missing Values](fts-sort-null) and
[Sort Arrays with Multiple Types](fts-sort-arrays-multiple-types).

**Input:**

```json
db.users.aggregate([
  {
    "$search": {
      "text": {
        "path": "b",
        "query": "hello"
      },
      "sort": {
        "c": 1
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "$project": {
      "_id": 1,
      "c": 1,
      "score": { "$meta": "searchScore" }
    }
  }
])
```

**Output:**

```js
[
  { _id: 4, c: null, score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  { _id: 5, c: [], score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  { _id: 6, score: 0.025981096550822258 }
  { _id: 7, c: [ false, null, 15 ], score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  { _id: 2, c: 'foo', score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  {
    _id: 3,
    c: UUID('3be11d4e-62cb-4e95-9a3c-5c9f1e56c732'),
    score: 0.025981096550822258
  },
  {
    _id: 0,
    c: ObjectId('507f1f77bcf86cd799439011'),
    score: 0.025981096550822258
  },
  { _id: 1, c: true, score: 0.025981096550822258 }
]
```

The order of documents with `"_id": 4`, `"_id": 5`, `"_id": 6`, and `"_id": 7`
is random because MongoDB Search treats null and missing values as equal
when sorting.

**Descending-sort:**

Descending Sort

For a descending sort, MongoDB Search uses the element with the
highest BSON (Binary Javascript Object Notation) type to represent the multi-typed array.
MongoDB Search uses `false` to represent the multi-typed array for
the document with `_id: 7`, as this is the highest BSON (Binary Javascript Object Notation) type
in the array. Since MongoDB Search also ranks `true` values above `false` values,
MongoDB Search returns this document after the document with `_id: 1`.

To learn more, see [Sort by Null and Missing Values](fts-sort-null) and
[Sort Arrays with Multiple Types](fts-sort-arrays-multiple-types).

**Input:**

```json
db.users.aggregate([
  {
    "$search": {
      "text": {
        "path": "b",
        "query": "hello"
      },
      "sort": {
        "c": -1
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "$project": {
      "_id": 1,
      "c": 1,
      "score": { "$meta": "searchScore" }
    }
  }
])
```

**Output:**

```js
[
  { _id: 1, c: true, score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  { _id: 7, c: [ false, null, 15 ], score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  {
    _id: 0,
    c: ObjectId('507f1f77bcf86cd799439011'),
    score: 0.025981096550822258
  },
  {
    _id: 3,
    c: UUID('3be11d4e-62cb-4e95-9a3c-5c9f1e56c732'),
    score: 0.025981096550822258
  },
  { _id: 2, c: 'foo', score: 0.025981096550822258 }
  { _id: 4, c: null, score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  { _id: 5, c: [], score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  { _id: 6, score: 0.025981096550822258 },
]
```

The order of documents with `"_id": 4`, `"_id": 5`, and `"_id": 6`
is random because MongoDB Search treats null and missing values as equal
when sorting.

**Nodata-highest:**

`noData: highest`

The following queries specify `noData: highest`
to set null values as the highest BSON (Binary Javascript Object Notation) type during sorting.

**Ascending-sort:**

Ascending Sort

For an ascending sort, MongoDB Search uses the element with the
lowest BSON (Binary Javascript Object Notation) type to represent the multi-typed array.
The query specifies `noData: highest` to consider
null or missing values as the highest BSON (Binary Javascript Object Notation) value, so
MongoDB Search uses `15` to represent the multi-typed array for
the document with `_id: 7` since numbers are the next
lowest BSON (Binary Javascript Object Notation) type in the array.

To learn more, see [Sort by Null and Missing Values](fts-sort-null) and
[Sort Arrays with Multiple Types](fts-sort-arrays-multiple-types).

**Input:**

```json
db.users.aggregate([
  {
    "$search": {
      "text": {
        "path": "b",
        "query": "hello"
      },
      "sort": {
        "c": {
          "order": 1,
          "noData": "highest"
        }
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "$project": {
      "_id": 1,
      "c": 1,
      "score": { "$meta": "searchScore" }
    }
  }
])
```

**Output:**

```js
[
  { _id: 7, c: [ false, null, 15 ], score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  { _id: 2, c: 'foo', score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  {
    _id: 3,
    c: UUID('3be11d4e-62cb-4e95-9a3c-5c9f1e56c732'),
    score: 0.025981096550822258
  },
  {
    _id: 0,
    c: ObjectId('507f1f77bcf86cd799439011'),
    score: 0.025981096550822258
  },
  { _id: 1, c: true, score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  { _id: 4, c: null, score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  { _id: 5, c: [], score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  { _id: 6, score: 0.025981096550822258 }
]
```

The order of documents with `"_id": 4`, `"_id": 5`, and `"_id": 6`
is random because MongoDB Search treats null and missing values as equal
when sorting.

**Descending-sort:**

Descending Sort

For a descending sort, MongoDB Search uses the element with the
highest BSON (Binary Javascript Object Notation) type to represent the multi-typed array.
Since the query specifies the `noData` field as `highest`
to set null or missing values as the highest BSON (Binary Javascript Object Notation) value,
MongoDB Search uses `null` to represent the multi-typed array for
the document with `_id: 7` and returns this document at
the top of the results along
with other null and missing values.

To learn more, see [Sort by Null and Missing Values](fts-sort-null) and
[Sort Arrays with Multiple Types](fts-sort-arrays-multiple-types).

**Input:**

```json
db.users.aggregate([
  {
    "$search": {
      "text": {
        "path": "b",
        "query": "hello"
      },
      "sort": {
        "c": {
          "order": -1,
          "noData": "highest"
        }
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "$project": {
      "_id": 1,
      "c": 1,
      "score": { "$meta": "searchScore" }
    }
  }
])
```

**Output:**

```js
[
  { _id: 4, c: null, score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  { _id: 5, c: [], score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  { _id: 6, score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  { _id: 7, c: [ false, null, 15 ], score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  { _id: 1, c: true, score: 0.025981096550822258 },
  {
    _id: 0,
    c: ObjectId('507f1f77bcf86cd799439011'),
    score: 0.025981096550822258
  },
  {
    _id: 3,
    c: UUID('3be11d4e-62cb-4e95-9a3c-5c9f1e56c732'),
    score: 0.025981096550822258
  },
  { _id: 2, c: 'foo', score: 0.025981096550822258 }
]
```

The order of documents with `"_id": 4`, `"_id": 5`, `"_id": 6`, and `"_id": 7`
is random because MongoDB Search treats null and missing values as equal
when sorting.
